The mean is widely used but is sensitive to outliers.

Median

The median is the middle value when the data is arranged in ascending order.

If the number of observations is odd, the median is the center value.
If even, it is the average of the two middle values.

The median is robust to outliers and is useful for skewed data.

Minimum and Maximum
Minimum: Smallest value in the dataset
Maximum: Largest value in the dataset

These measures indicate the range of observed values.

2. Measures of Variability

Measures of variability describe how spread out the data is.

Range
Range=Maximum−Minimum

Variance
Variance measures the average squared deviation from the mean.

σ2=n∑(xi−xˉ)2
	​

Standard Deviation

Standard deviation is the square root of variance and is expressed in the same units as the original data.

A larger standard deviation indicates greater dispersion.

3. Percentiles and Quartiles

A percentile indicates the value below which a given percentage of observations fall.

Important percentiles:

25th percentile (Q1)
50th percentile (Median or Q2)
75th percentile (Q3)

Quartiles divide the dataset into four equal parts.

4. Grouped Statistics

In many datasets, numerical variables are analyzed within categories.

Example:

Categorical Variable: Sex
Numerical Variable: Age

Using grouping, we can compute mean, median, min, max, and standard deviation for each category separately. This allows comparison between groups.

